post_text:
Though you probably know her already, CCHS would like to welcome Mrs. Valerie Johnson over to the high school! She will be taking over the library this year and is T-Bird through and through. Learn more about Valerie in her own words:

"I’ve been married to Coy for 25 years. We have two kids Brayden (22), Sara (18), a daughter-in-law Summer, and a fur baby, Tilley. We are a farming family, so I love anything outdoors, shopping, being with family, road trips, and anything T-Birds. The saying, 'Once a T-Bird, always a T-Bird' is strong in our family because we are a third generation Thunderbird family and have several nieces and a nephew that are Thunderbirds. This is my 13th year at a place I call 'home'!"

Welcome to the high school!

The Junior High and Senior High Football games against Harrisburg tomorrow (Saturday, August 29th) have been cancelled due to a positive COVID-19 test within the program.

This is disappointing news for our athletes who have worked hard to have the opportunity to play. We appreciate Thunderbird Nation’s positive support for our team in the midst of a situation outside of their control and look forward the rest of our season when we are able to get back on the field. #TBirdStrong

post_text:
As the week closes, we have pivoted two additional classrooms to online learning for the next fourteen days. We want to thank our teachers and staff for their hard work with our in-person, blended, and virtual learners. Our staff has been here extra hours, covering additional duties, and doing everything possible so we can stay in school.

We will soon be starting our meal routes for virtual learners. If any family learning virtually would like to be added to food routes, please call the school office as soon as possible. Meal routes will also be used to distribute jump drives and supplies for our students without internet.

We are so grateful for our parents and community members for their unconditional support. They have taken the challenges of this week in stride. We will get through this together! #TBirdStrong

Important football announcement:

Due to the massive amounts of rain that is forecasted for today and the early evening, tonight’s Sr High Football game with Harrisburg has been rescheduled for tomorrow(Saturday) at 7:00pm. The game will be played at Harrisburg. We will play the Jr high game that was postponed last night (Thursday) at 3:00 at Harrisburg. The stadium will be cleared between games and fans will have to pay to re-enter.

Both games will return to Cross County in 2021.

We hope to see you all on Saturday supporting the Thunderbirds. Please wear your masks and be prepared to practice social distancing.

Since March 16th, our amazing Aramark team has served over 89,170 meals to our students at home during school closure. Please help us thank them for their unbelievable work on the front lines!

We are committed to continuing to feed our students who have chosen fully virtual learning for the 2020-2021 school year! Virtual students can elect to receive a week's worth of meals (breakfast and lunch) delivered to their door. If you are interested in receiving meals, please call your building office to sign up! More information (including schedules and delivery days) will be released as soon as possible. #proudTBirds #inittogether #TbirdStrong

post_text:
Virtual Parent Meeting TONIGHT at 6:00 PM in the CCETA Cafeteria

ADDITIONAL INFORMATION:

Due to ADH and DESE guidelines, this event is limited to the first 100 parents. Please limit attendance to only one parent per household if possible to give the most people the chance to attend. Overflow rooms may be used if necessary.

Masks or face coverings are required.

This event is for parents signed up for or considering the fully virtual learning option only. If you have questions about in-person learning or masks, please call your child's principal or school office.

9-12 grade students may attend the meeting if their participation will assist in the decision making process.

No matter if your child sits in our four walls or at your home this year, we know that they are our future. We are excited to serve and educate ALL of our students, on our campus, online, and as always, on purpose.

We’ve polled our Seniors about graduation, and 50% have voted to continue with our July 25th outdoor graduation ceremony even with strict health guidelines, social distancing, and limitations on ceremony time and size as mandated by the Arkansas Department of Elementary and Secondary Education. Graduation is scheduled to begin at 8:30 AM.

Graduation practice will be Friday, July 24th at 9:30 AM and is required for any Senior wishing to walk at graduation. Tickets for the ceremony will be distributed at practice. Please meet at the front of the field house entrance, socially distance, and, as ordered by Governor Hutchinson today, wear a mask. #SeniorStrong #Classof2020

post_text:
Our administrative team is working to release an updated school calendar in light of the start date adjustment. School will now begin on August 24th. Unfortunately, since the Governor has required school to start three weeks after our original date, we will not have a Fall (October) Break this year.

Look out for more information and a Virtual Learning Information Night for parents in the coming weeks!

post_text:
We are excited to begin school in-person this Fall and look forward to seeing our students on-campus! After your strong responses from our parent survey in May, we learned that you appreciate our frequent communication and hope you continue to engage with us as we ramp up our updates on school reopening.

To start, please fill out this survey by Friday, June 26th about the 2020-2021 school year. Submit one response per student and let us know if your student plans to join us in-person or may need fully virtual learning to accommodate individual health and academic needs. As you fill out your survey, please note that your responses are non-binding and that additional information will be released in the coming weeks on what both in-person and fully virtual learning will look like after the analysis of your survey responses.

https://forms.gle/pvy2fB8aJU5HP4oa7

A few years ago, Cross County School District began providing all students with free breakfast and lunch through the Community Eligibility Provision (CEP) and the USDA. Since we applied for CEP, our families are eligible for this free support through Pandemic SNAP! We care about our students and their families and are grateful to be a small part of this relief program—according to DHS, you should receive your EBT card late this month.

For more information, check the link below or the FAQ image in the comments! #CCcares #proudTBirds

All students participating in sports and cheer at Cross County School District must have a current physical in order to participate in the 2020-2021 season. ARcare will be providing free physicals on the following dates:

3rd-6th grade: June 2-4

Forms to be completed will be available at each campus to complete prior to your appointment. Please call ARcare at 870-442-2040 to make your appointment!

post_text:
Our Food Service team is still hard at work preparing food! Tuesday deliveries cover both Tuesday and Wednesday and Thursday deliveries cover Thursday, Friday, and Monday meals.

If you haven't received food and would like meals, please call us so we can get you set up! All children under 18 are also welcome to pick up meals at our two Wynne drop-off points, the Old Junior High and Caldwell Pharmacy. We preplan how many meals to bring, so if you're new to our food service just give us a call so we can up our count! #proudTBirds

post_text:
Seniors,

The time is nearing for your individual graduations next week. If you have not made your appointment, please call us to do so. As you prepare for your day, please take note of a few expectations:

1. Please wear slacks, khakis, or dresses, but no jeans.
2. Please wear dress shoes. If you wear boots, please be sure they are clean.
3. You may need to steam your gown.
4. Make sure all dues, fines, or charges are paid before receiving your diploma.
5. Be sure to turn in your computer, jerseys, and uniforms before receiving your diploma.

We want next week to be special for each of you and we are excited to get to see everyone. If you have any questions, please give us a call at the school.

We know that the Pandemic has caused economic upheaval all over our country and want to help you navigate any changes you may be experiencing!

If your family has questions about SNAP benefits or the application process, the Arkansas Department of Human Services is providing a call center to assist you! SNAP benefits can provide qualifying households food for their families during the COVID-19 pandemic. Filling out the application for SNAP benefits families and our food service team in providing you with healthy, high-quality meals.

The hotline number is 1-833-762-7275 and is available Monday-Friday, from 10:00 AM-3:00 PM.

Ready for a work out with Mrs. Amy? Here we go!

10 Jumping Jacks
10 Plank Jacks
10 Burpees
10 squats with shoulder press
10 Lunges- 5 on each leg
10 Side arm raises
10 Sumo squats
*Do all 7 exercises and then repeat 2 or 3 times. Rest two minutes in between.

Make sure you try one of Mrs. Amy's Daily Challenges:
Monday- Walk for 20 minutes
Tuesday- Ride a bicycle for 20 minutes
Wednesday- Play your favorite sport for 20 minutes
Thursday- Jog for 5 minutes/walk 5 minutes
Friday- Play your favorite sport for 20 minutes

We had to get creative but there is now limited Wifi Access in Bay Village! Students can access the Wifi Network CrossWifiMobile using the password crosscrossmobile at the Bay Village Fire Station. You will have the best service at the fire station if you are closer to the white CCSD school van parked in the lot.

Due to limitations around cell coverage in Bay Village, this Wifi signal is not as fast as our other access points but it can download tutorials, videos, school work, and assignments if given enough time! We hope this additional point helps our students as they begin virtual learning this week! #techyTBirds #thunderbirds #TBirdstrong

Beginning next week, Cross County High School will shift to Virtual Learning. Students will access their material through Echo the same way they do at school. Each teacher will have assignments and turn in instructions on their Echo agendas for students to work on from home. Teachers are available to answer any questions about their work during school days from 8:00 AM to 3:30 PM. All staff emails are available here: https://www.crosscountyschools.com/staff

The following guidance document explains what students can expect.

Teachers and staff members have been reaching out to every student this week to check in. If you have not heard from anyone at CCHS and have a question about Virtual Learning, please message or email us with your contact information so we can get back to you right away!

Thank you for your support and flexibility as we work together to keep learning during this extended school closure. #TBirdStrong #proudTBirds

As today comes to a close, we want to take a moment to thank our food service team, bus drivers, coaches, aides, volunteer teachers, and administrators who helped us make and deliver 947 breakfasts and 1,369 lunches this week! Their willingness to get up early, navigate muddy roads, and knock on doors have allowed us to feed nearly 50% of our students. Times of crisis often reveal the best of us, and we are forever grateful for these hometown heroes.

We will continue to feed students next week during lunch time. Lunch meals will include breakfast for the next morning.

Thank you to EVERYONE for your support. We are #tbirdstrong!

post_text:
This afternoon, Governor Asa Hutchinson announced a statewide closure of all K-12 school buildings as a response to the national health emergency. Therefore, Cross County School District will be closed tomorrow and the rest of this week. We will utilize AMI Days 1-4.

As a reminder, Cross County School District will be closed Friday, March 20th - Friday, March 27th for Spring Break.

Please continue to monitor our district website and Facebook page for updates. Information on food delivery for students and any additional AMI days will be available by 6:00 PM tonight.

We are grateful for your support in taking this necessary step to protect our students, families, and our community at large.

post_text: Recently, students from Cross County High School traveled to Jonesboro for the Daughter's of the American Revolution Essay Awards ceremony where ten students were awarded for their achievements of academic excellence in writing. Students in grade seven were asked to write as if they were a Pilgrim and how they would have changed their choices on land to better help the colonists to survive. The winners for this category are as follows: first place, Lainey wood; Caleb second place, Caleb Shirley; third place tie, Gunner Land, Hayleigh Wilson, Hank Bostick; honorable mention, Bella Bowles, Knoa Roberts. Ninth grade students were asked to write as a crew member and evaluate the choices of Christopher Columbus' first voyage. The winners for this category are as follows: first place, Conner McGee; third place, Grant McCommon; honorable mention, Alston Venzen. Our teachers, staff, and parents are all extremely proud of the accomplishments of these students and all those students from our school that participated in the contest. We truly have exceptional students at Cross County!

We want your Kindergartener or Pre-K students at CCETA!

Did you know you can choose to send your incoming kindergartener to our school even if you do not live in our school district boundaries? You can! School Choice Applications will be available on-site!

Required Documents for Kindergarten Registration:
- Birth Certificate
- Social Security Card
- Proof of Residency (utility bill)
- Up-to-date Immunizations/Shot Records

Required Documents for Pre-K Registration:
- Birth Certificate
- Social Security Card
- Proof of Income (1 month’s check stubs, W2, or Tax Return)
- Up-to-date Immunizations/Shot Records

Questions? For Pre-K call 870-588-6843. For Kindergarten call 870-588-3337.

post_text: To recognize the important job of a school counselor, Governor Asa Hutchinson has proclaimed February 3rd through February 7th, 2020 as National School Counseling Week in Arkansas. CCSD would like to take this opportunity to recognize our two outstanding school counselors for their dedication to our students. Mrs. Susan Morgan, high school counselor with 18 years in education, and Mrs. Carol Crow, elementary counselor with 31 years in education, both prove everyday that they are here for our students. We could not ask for two better people for the job. Thank you for all you do!

post_text:
Governor Asa Hutchinson has issued a proclamation declaring January 26th- February 1st Arkansas School Choice Week!

Every parent in Arkansas has the choice of where to send their child to school and we invite you to consider our district. Cross County Elementary has earned back-to-back ‘A’ school letter grades and is the perfect choice for a child looking for individualized, rigorous math and literacy instruction in a small, family-like atmosphere. For students in grades 7-12, Cross County High School is home to a Founder’s Award Finalist EAST Program, a nationally recognized College and Career Access Program, and innovative technology practices on one-to-one Apple technology.

We want to share our amazing schools with you— call 870-588-3337 to schedule a tour or to find out more about Cross County School District! If you are ready to join our Thunderbird family, applications for school choice are due May 1st and can be downloaded at crosscountyschools.com!

post_text: Way to go EAST at Cross County High School!
shared_text:
EAST at Cross County High School
January 25 at 3:00 PM ·

We are excited to announce Alexis Lace, Grant King, Harrison McGee, and Stormie Watts as the winners of the 2019 Congressional App Challenge! Their winning submission, the Parker Homestead Visit App, was originally created as a product for the Smithsonian’s Museums on Main Street program. On Friday, the team met with Congressman Rick Crawford to demonstrate their app and show off its features. We are extremely proud of this team and the students who played supporting roles throughout this project. We are also thankful for Congressman Crawford’s continued support of this competition and the Parker Homestead for partnering with us on this project. The Parker Homestead Visit App is available now for download on any iOS device on the Apple App Store.

shared_text:
Arkansas Rural Education Association
October 29, 2019 at 12:25 PM ·

Arkansas Rural Education Association is spotlighting the Cross County School District! With an enrollment of 580 Cross County School District is in the Crowley's Ridge Coop area in Cross County and employs 81 people there. The Cross County School District prides itself as being the only district in the state to implement the TAP System for teacher support and evaluation. Both Cross County Elementary and High School offer students innovative learning opportunities through project based learning, school wide learning outcomes, and real-world learning activities. Other highlights of the district include and award-winning EAST program, a nationally recognized College and Career Access Program sending more students to college than the national average, and one-to-one Apple technology. To find out more about the district, visit their website at www.crosscountyschools.com or follow them on facebook at www.facebook.com/CrossCountySD.

post_text: Under Mrs. Nikki Williams’s leadership, CCHS’s Thunderbirds Against Drugs (TAD) group was awarded a grant from The Arkansas Sheriff’s Association to purchase materials and supplies to help the student group meet its goals and fund Red Ribbon Week. We would like to thank Cross County Sheriff, David West for the opportunity so we can continue to grow student leaders and bring awareness to all students.

post_text: The halters have been hung; the pens have been cleaned. The livestock show season has ended for our Cross County team. All the laughs and tears will be cherished and remembered for these girls have worked hard for all the memories they will treasure. State fair was a blast and they learned many valuable lessons. Samantha Hagler won best-of-breed with her Dutch rabbit. She also placed top six out of the state in Dairy goat showmanship. Camryn Scott placed 9th and 13th with her market lambs and she also got pulled for showmanship. Lily showed well with her Berkshire Hog.
